cs.IT, cs.CR, cs.DC, cs.CE, cs.NE 

The paper deals with the problem of encoding information using DNA sequences, which can be seen as a digital communications problem. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the issue of mutations in DNA sequences, which can be seen as a security concern, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely category. The paper also involves the use of coding and noncoding DNA host sequences, which can be related to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) and cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science). Finally, the paper draws inferences with respect to the biological implications of some of the results presented, which can be related to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
